properties.Title: Heat Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: First heat event of the season continues this week. Temperatures will soar to near the thirty degree mark today and Wednesday. Indications suggest above normal temperatures near thirty again on Thursday. Humidex values in the mid to upper thirties will prevail each afternoon. Some relief is expected near the shorelines of the Great Lakes. A cold front will deliver considerably cooler and less humid air to Southern Ontario on Friday. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. The risks are greater for young children, pregnant women, older adults, people with chronic illnesses and people working or exercising outdoors. Heat warnings are issued when very high temperature or humidity conditions are expected to pose an elevated risk of heat illnesses, such as heat stroke or heat exhaustion. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada. To report severe weather, send an email to ONstorm@canada.ca or tweet reports using #ONStorm.

properties.Title: Alberta Emergency Alert - High Water Level Alert
properties.Summary:
Description: The Pembina and Paddles Rivers are experiencing high water levels due to spring melt and significant precipitation. As a result, several County roads have been closed and overland flooding is occurring in certain areas. With the forecasted precipitation, rivers are expected to continue to rise. Residents are asked to exercise extreme caution around any water body. ### Go to https://511.alberta.ca for up to date Road Report information. Visit www.countybarrhead.ab.ca for further information.

properties.Title: Severe Thunderstorm Warning In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: At 2:21 p.m. MDT, Environment Canada meteorologists are tracking a severe thunderstorm capable of producing very strong wind gusts, up to toonie size hail and heavy rain. This severe thunderstorm is currently located near Bindloss and is tracking to the east at 30 km/h. ### Heavy downpours can cause flash floods and water pooling on roads. Large hail can damage property and cause injury. Strong wind gusts can toss loose objects, damage weak buildings, break branches off trees and overturn large vehicles. Severe thunderstorm warnings are issued when imminent or occurring thunderstorms are likely to produce or are producing one or more of the following: large hail, damaging winds, torrential rainfall.

properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Smoke from a forest fire near Havre Boucher area of Antigonish County is causing a reduction in visibility and air quality over areas in its vicinity and downwind towards Highway 104 and into western Cape Breton. Locations: Havre Boucher and surrounding areas, including downwind areas in eastern Antigonish county and southern Inverness County. Wind forecast: southwest 20 to 40 km/h this evening, diminishing to light overnight. Winds 10 to 20 km/h and variable in direction on Wednesday. Winds increasing on Thursday to southwest 20 to 40 km/h. Remarks: The fire is still out of control as of this afternoon but 50 percent contained. it covers an area of about 150 Hectares. ### Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.

properties.Summary:
Description: First heat event of the season continues. High daytime temperatures hit near 30 this afternoon with Humidex values in the mid to upper thirties. These conditions are expected to return Wednesday afternoon, before a slow-moving cold front approaches from the northwest on Thursday bringing showers and cooler air. ### Extreme heat affects everyone. The risks are greater for young children, pregnant women, older adults, people with chronic illnesses and people working or exercising outdoors. Heat warnings are issued when very high temperature or humidity conditions are expected to pose an elevated risk of heat illnesses, such as heat stroke or heat exhaustion. properties.Title: Special Air Quality Statement In Effect
properties.Summary:
Description: Smoke from a forest fire near Sabbies River is causing a reduction in air quality due to smoke in its vicinity and areas downwind to the east and northeast. Locations: Sabbies River to Rogersville and vicinity. Satellite imagery this morning showed smoke stretching eastward over an area roughly between Richibucto and Miramichi all the way to the coast. Short range wind forecast: Southwesterly 20 to 40 km/h diminishing this evening. On Wednesday, winds are forecast to be 10 to 20 km/h and variable in direction. Remarks: The forest fire is still out of control this afternoon and is covering an estimated area of 350 hectares as reported by New Brunswick Natural resources and Energy Development. More information will be provided as it becomes available. ### Visit www.airhealth.ca for information on how to reduce your health risk and your personal contribution to pollution levels, as well as for current and forecast AQHI values. Please continue to monitor alerts and forecasts issued by Environment Canada.
